description: Borrowed from Latin vermiculatus (“inlaid in wavy lines”), past participle of vermiculor (“to be full of worms or worm-eaten”), from vermiculus (“little worm”).

adjectives.description: vermiculate (comparative more vermiculate, superlative most vermiculate)

entries.meaning: Like a worm; resembling a worm.

verbs.description: vermiculate (third-person singular simple present vermiculates, present participle vermiculating, simple past and past participle vermiculated)

entries.meaning: To decorate with lines resembling the tracks of worms.
